  "doc_id": "60647",
  "text": "Three studies detected associations between built environmental factors and health outcomes independent from neighbourhood SEP and individual factors. A walkability index was inversely associated with mental quality of life and positively with more depressive symptoms [CITATION_1] . One study found a negative association between traffic and a health score calculated from self-reported health problems. Higher values of the score indicated better health [CITATION_2] . In another study waste sites and traffic were positively associated with reported day-to-day stress [CITATION_3] .",
